  1. No, with the only information on median arrival delay, we cannot say ExpressJet is a more reliable airline, because we only have the middle observations, and we do not know what’s the arrival delay time of other flights. To gain more exhaustive sense of the reliable airlines, we need to know the mean, median, mode, standard deviation, max and min.

  2. Mean: the average arrival delay time of flights; Mode: the most occurred arrival delay time; Standard deviation: the variation of average arrival delay time; Max: the max arrival delay time; Min: the min arrival delay time.

  3. Out of all the carriers, F9 has the highest average and mean arrival delay time and its standard deviation, or the variation of arrival delay time is relatively large as well, which means the time is not very predictable. However, the number of observations for F9 is relatively smaller, which means the results might not be valid enough comparing to large number of observations of other carriers.

library(dplyr)
mode <- function(x) {
  ux <- unique(x)
  ux[which.max(tabulate(match(x, ux)))]
}

noncancelled %>% 
  group_by(carrier) %>%
  summarise(
    n=n(),
    mean_arrdelay=mean(arr_delay),
    mode_arrdelay=mode(arr_delay),
    med_arrdelay=median(arr_delay),
    max_arrdelay=max(arr_delay),
    min_arrdelay=min(arr_delay),
    sd_arrdelay=sd(arr_delay)
  )

  flights,
  is.na(dep_delay),
  is.na(arr_delay))

cancelled_each_day <- cancelled %>%
  group_by(date) %>%
  summarise(n_cancelled = n())

all_each_day <- flights %>%
  group_by(date) %>% 
  summarise(n_total = n())

cancel <- merge(cancelled_each_day, all_each_day, by = "date", sort = TRUE, all.y = TRUE)
cancel [is.na(cancel)] <- 0 
cancel$cancel_rate =100*( cancel$ n_cancelled / cancel$n_total)
ggplot(cancel, aes(x=date, y=cancel_rate)) + 
    geom_bar(stat="identity")

1.3.2 EDA: Navigating NAs

  1. Missing values are dropped in a histogram. In bar chart, missing values are included in a discrete category. There is a difference because “x” argument needs to be continuous, numeric values in a histogram so that observations can be grouped into bins while “x” can be categorical in a bar chart.

  2. na.rm = TRUE removes “NA” values from the observations that mean() and sum() are going to make calculation on so that mean() and sum() can calculate the values of variables without “NA”.

2.1 Choose a month

  1. According to the plot, we can see that the average delays in October is the lowest, with an average of 9-minute delay. Every month except July, August and December, are at least 80% of flights on-time.
gby_month <- CHIflights %>% group_by(MONTH) 

arrdelays <- 
  gby_month %>%
  summarise(avg_arrdelay       = mean(ARR_DELAY, na.rm = TRUE),
            avg_arrdelay_new   = mean(ARR_DELAY_NEW, na.rm = TRUE),
            prop_ontime        = 1-sum(ARR_DEL15,na.rm = TRUE)/n(),
            n_flights = n()
  )

ggplot(arrdelays, aes(x = MONTH)) +

  geom_line(aes(y = avg_arrdelay_new / 20), color = "blue") +
  scale_x_discrete(limits = c(1:12)) +
  scale_y_continuous(
    breaks = c(.2, .4, .6, .8, 1),
    sec.axis = sec_axis(~. * 20,
      name = "mean delay (line) "
    )
  ) +
  labs(y = " Proportion of on time flights (bar)")

2.2 Pick an airline

  1. I would recommend AS. Because the probablity of an AS flight to be late is the lowest and the mean delay time of an AS flight is shortest. In addition, even an AS flights is late, the delay is unlikely to be extremly long and is usually within 350 minutes, making the situation more controlable.

I prefer the sophisticated one because it gives more information about the airline such as the dispersion of the delay and makes us have more confidence on the recommedation we make.

gby_carr <-
  CHIflights %>%
  group_by(OP_UNIQUE_CARRIER)

sum_carr <-
  gby_carr %>%
  summarise(n_cflights = n(), 
            n_delay = sum(ARR_DEL15, na.rm = TRUE), 
            p_delay = n_delay / n_cflights, 
            mean_delay = mean(ARR_DELAY_NEW, na.rm = TRUE), 
            max_delay = max(ARR_DELAY_NEW, na.rm = TRUE))

# basic
sum_carr %>%
  ggplot() + geom_col(mapping = aes(x = reorder(OP_UNIQUE_CARRIER, p_delay), y = p_delay))

# sophisticated
graph_sop <-
  ggplot(sum_carr) +
  geom_col(mapping = aes(
    x = reorder(OP_UNIQUE_CARRIER, mean_delay),
    y = p_delay * 10000,
    color = OP_UNIQUE_CARRIER
  )) +
  geom_boxplot(
    data = gby_carr,
    mapping = aes(x = OP_UNIQUE_CARRIER, y = ARR_DELAY_NEW)
  ) +
  geom_point(aes(
    x = OP_UNIQUE_CARRIER,
    y = mean_delay,
    color = OP_UNIQUE_CARRIER
  )) +
  scale_y_continuous(sec.axis = sec_axis(trans = ~. / 10000, name = "p_delay")) +
  labs(y = "arr_delay")

2.3 Reconsider the date?

  1. New recommendation would be November. Because in November, the average arrival delay of flights from Greer and that of all the flights to Chicago are rather low.In addtion, the proportion of on time flights from Greer and that of all the flights to Chicago are also relatively higher.

It is superior to the old recommedarion because new ranking factors have been taken into consideration and the needs of most important members and the rest of participants are balanced in the new recommendation.

gre_flights <- 
  CHIflights %>% 
  filter(ORIGIN_CITY_NAME=="Greer, SC") %>%
  group_by(MONTH)

gre_delays <- 
  gre_flights %>%
  summarise(gre_mean_delay = mean(ARR_DELAY_NEW, na.rm = TRUE),
            prop_ontime    = 1-sum(ARR_DEL15,na.rm = TRUE)/n(),
            )

graph_gre <- 
  ggplot(gre_delays, aes(x = MONTH)) +
  geom_col(aes(y = prop_ontime)) +
  geom_line(aes(y = gre_mean_delay/35), color ="blue") +
  scale_x_discrete(limits=c(1:12)) +
  scale_y_continuous(sec.axis = sec_axis(~.*35,
                     name     = "mean delay - Greer (line) "
                    )) +
  labs(y = "ontime proportion - Greer (bar)")

graph_whole <-
  ggplot(arrdelays, aes(x = MONTH)) +
  geom_col(aes(y = prop_ontime)) +

  scale_x_discrete(limits=c(1:12)) +
  scale_y_continuous(sec.axis = sec_axis(~.*20,
                     name     = "mean delay (line) "
